column1: https://i1.sndcdn.com/artworks-000652303669-pgyy6z-large.jpg	2017-12-02T23:24:50Z	"Alice DiMicele has been a grassroots trailblazer in independent music for over 30 years. Bucking the advances of record labels early on in her career
column2: she has since self-released 14 albums on her own Alice Otter Music label
column3: including her latest One With The Tide (Release date: Jan. 19th
column4: 2018). While seamlessly working jazz/blues phrasing and R&B and rock & roll rhythms into a broadened Folk/ Roots/Americana sound she describes as ""Organic Acoustic Groove
column5: she has stayed true to herself and her mission

column7: inspiring them to take a stand for love
column9: and for justice in the world.

column5: Jenny Conlee-Drizos (piano

column1: The emotive sounds of Jenny Conlee-Drizos (The
Decemberists) Hammond B3 drift along with the current on the title track “One With The Tide
column2: ” a tune that equates the mysterious twists and turns that life presents
column3: with the pull of the moon and changing of the tides. The dynamic range of DiMicele’s vocal depth is on full display on the bluesy “Desire
column4: ” and the soulful reworked “The Other Side” from her 2000 “Alice Live” album. Tackling the complexities of addiction
column5: “Lonely Alone” expresses the experience of being in love with an alcoholic and the feelings of loneliness that often comes with the package. The upbeat calypso inspired “Waiting” is a highly danceable tune
column6: sure to pick ones spirits up. “Nature Reigns” expresses the intrinsic value and beauty of the natural world and “Seeds” reminds of the connection between what we create and what we experience. “Voice of the Water” confirms DiMicele’s environmental commitment
column7: with a call to action in solidarity with water protectors everywhere
column8: while John Lennon’s “Imagine” is just as timely a vision for humanity as ever.

column1: https://i1.sndcdn.com/artworks-000045508648-m6rsun-large.jpg	2013-04-14T20:25:50Z	"Performing or writing songs with someone will inevitably bring you closer to them. Whether it's touring in a smelly van for three weeks or trying to finish a gem of a song with that last killer line
column2: there's a lot to absorb
column3: tolerate and learn about your fellow musical comrades in those twilight hours
column4: much like how a family gives each other unconditional love
column5: despite not having the choice to be together. But imagine working with someone in such close quarters and only later finding out that you're indeed related. Such a remarkable story happened to the core of local revivalists Jenny Dragon
column6: and it's only made their unique vision stronger.

column1: We begin in 1997
column2: when Jenny Dragon vocalists Jodi Jean Amble and Sarah Goldstein were both theatre majors at LaCrosse
column3: WI's Viterbo University. ""Sarah was a couple of years behind me in school and from the beginning of our friendship
column4: I always referred to her as my younger sister
column5: says Amble. The pair appeared in a school production of Chekov's Three Sisters as well. Amble recalls
column6: ""I was Irina and Sarah was Masha... Irina is hopeful and full of life and Masha is dark and brooding (to generalize). Jenny Dragon has self described our music as 'heavy whimsy' and Sarah and I have often mused that Sarah brings more of the heavy and I bring more of the whimsy.""

column1: The duo lived in Chicago together briefly
column2: but different paths seperated them for much longer
column3: including a stint for Amble to teach English in South Korea and Goldstein's relocation to Colorado for a winter. Eight years passed and eventually in 2009
column4: after a one-off performance together in Spring Green
column5: WI
column6: they decided to make a go of it as a fully-functioning band
column7: and Jenny Dragon was born. Amble and Goldstein then each contributed band members into the fold: Goldstein met her guitarist fiance Brian Sharpe while working together
column8: and he fronts his own Brian Sharpe and the Associates; bassist Ed Sullivan had played with Amble in a gypsy-jazz act; Goldstein had collaborated with guitarist Drew Pompano in a duo called Square the Circle; drummer Janet Cramer came from Amble's bossa nova group and her own Jodi Jean Band
column9: and brings plenty of Latin and blues experience to the group; violinist Cathy Starr and banjo player Phil Vickers contributed to another project of Sharpe and Goldstein's (Derek Nelson and the Musicians) and before they knew it
column10: Jenny Dragon was an veritable army of veteran musicians.

column1: But it wasn't until this past summer that Goldstein and Amble discovered there was much more to their sister-like bond than expected. ""I was in Brule
column2: WI with my Mum Jane and Grandma Brunner (Dorothy)
column3: recalls Goldstein. ""Hanging out
column4: being eaten by mosquitos
column5: having some moonshine with Uncle Joe. Casually
column6: Mom was flipping through the Brunner genealogy - this is my late Grandpa Roman Brunner's side of the family
column8: WI area - and she came across the name Chuck Amble."" It turns out Chuck and his wife Judy were Jodi's godparents
column9: and Judy was Goldstein's mother's cousin. A once-in-a-lifetime coincidence was now just further proof that Jenny Dragon had a deeper reason for existing.

column1: The ""heavy whimsy"" on A Fair Souvenir is an incredibly fitting description for the enchanting mixture of dark humor and light-hearted jangle. The album's first proper track
column2: the hard-swinging ""Boom Boom
column3: takes on America's history with nuclear testing and the album's tongue-in-cheek nods to apocalyptic imagery don't end there. Whether it's in the grind of Starr's violin or the almost gothically operatic vocals that open ""Johnny Chapman
column4: there's a certain foreboding mystery throughout Souvenir that one can't help but get sucked into. Though nostalgic in its tone and presentation (the disc itself resembles a vinyl record
column5: and was recorded in just two days to 1/4-inch tape at Hi-Style Studio)
column6: it's far from gimmicky. In fact
column7: it raises a much deeper question: Is the Fair Souvenir the music itself - that sprung from Amble and Goldstein's unique bond - or is it the family ties that were discovered after starting Jenny Dragon? Either way
column8: both are genuinely newsworthy."	2013-04-14T20:25:50Z	1970590	all	Americanarockfolkish	4810089	True	playlist	Heavy Whimsy Music	2015-10-13T14:29:59Z	all-rights-reserved	[]	0	False	a-fair-souvenir	https://soundcloud.com/jenny-dragon/sets/a-fair-souvenir	True		iTunes	https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/a-fair-souvenir/id599643295	2013-02-15T00:00:00Z	[]	0		album	public		A Fair Souvenir	0	[]	https://api.soundcloud.com/playlists/4810089	32587268	32587268

column1: https://i1.sndcdn.com/artworks-000118502302-de0q9v-large.jpg	2014-11-09T04:48:03Z	"Chemical Burn finds that medicinal tonic poured of down n’ dirty
column2: riff chugging
column3: Groove Metal shaken with the machine gun pounding blasts of Death Metal and finished with a swig of Stoner Rock. There’s enough head banging
column4: crushingly heavy substance in this Bay Area band’s brew to invigorate the truest metal head
column5: with the tasty finish to attract a worldwide thirst.

column1: Can you imagine that full-contact party with Pantera and Machine Head in 1994 where Gene Hoglan was the bartender and Corrosion Of Conformity was the referee? That’s the sound that Chemical Burn has captured in a bottle – intense and raw.
The chemists behind this agent – Mike Garnica and Kevin Jackson – are the duo at the nucleus of Chemical Burn. On their second full-length album for MegaSonic
column2: Raining Anvils
column3: they spent the past year meticulously focusing on the songs – writing lyrics that mean something and arranging music that you can feel. Keeping their standards set to stun
column4: they recruited help from friend and Bay Area shredder
column5: Marc Pattison (Cirlce II Circle) to balance each song with next level solos that are like icing on top of a volcanic cake.

column1: To increase the potency of their formula
column2: the band joined producer Juan Urteaga (Testament
column3: Machine Head
column4: Exodus) at JingleTown studios in Oakland and created a beast of an album that is sure to make the folks from their legendary Bay Area scene proud. “We poured all we had into making these songs just right
column5: ” says Garnica with conviction
column6: “Every part was written with the intent to set the world on fire. Then we took them to Juan and he dumped jet fuel on them.”

column1: Setting it on fire had become the standard for whether or not an idea made the cut on the album. In doing so
column2: Garnica and Jackson tapped into the metal energy that their native Bay Area is known for
column3: while adding elements that make them every bit unique. The album opens with the brisk and raw
column4: ass kicking of “I Rise I Fly.” Snapping from blasting beats into crushing grooves that support a delicate dance of riff heavy guitars and choice vocal arrangements
column5: it’s an intoxicating anthem set ablaze and puffing a fierce pulse of smoke.

column1: “The album presents some pretty ugly real life situations that people can relate to – domestic violence
column2: police brutality
column3: losing a loved one
column4: ” the front man proclaims. “I Rise I Fly is about not just enduring those situations
column5: but coming out on top. And sonically
column6: it just sounds like you’re kicking the shit out of anything that dares to fuck with you.”

column1: Then there’s the breakout title track
column2: “Raining Anvils.” The guys release a downpour of devastating hooks
column3: fortified by blues riffing and a pounding triplet groove. “It’s like when you’re in one of those moods where nothing can faze you
column4: ” he continues. “Shit is dumping on you left and right
column5: but you know you got this.”

column1: After being friends for years and honing their craft in other projects
column2: the Garnica/Jackson duo would come together in Chemical Burn to produce astonishing results. They became so focused on their game plan that
column3: like surgeons
column4: they found themselves cutting out the fat and attending to the meaty guts of it all
column5: ultimately writing and recording the entirety of Raining Anvils themselves and restructuring Chemical Burn into the powerhouse that it is now.

column1: “Kev and I were instantly on the same page when it came to the writing process
column2: ” Garnica explains. “We’re just…bros. We both have great ideas to bring to the table but we check our egos at the door and just hash everything out. If a song doesn’t light us both up
column3: we go back to the drawing board with it. Eventually a light bulb goes off and it all comes together in a way that stokes the hell out of us. And then we’re bouncing off the walls.”

column1: Chemical Burn are young at heart
column2: but their experience shows that they’re capable of stomping a boot print in the world of Metal. Jackson toured as the drummer for Island DefJam recording artists
column3: Primer 55 on OzzFest in 2000 and has been a session drummer for various label artists
column4: while Garnica is a well-known musician in the Bay Area scene and gained industry insights as a guitar tech for Bay Area legends Testament
column5: Dragon Lord and Laaz Rocket. Forming the band in San Jose
column6: CA then moving to Los Angeles
column7: they rose through the local ranks in both markets with an explosive live presence that made them a fan favorite
column8: approaching every show with the same attitude – bring the intensity
column9: play your ass off and win the crowd over. But wait until folks get a load of what they’re doing on

column1: Along with the heaviness
column2: the band’s very name resembles the values presented in their messaging. “Chemical Burn is a metaphor for anything that you can be addicted to and burn out on
column3: but finding the strength to not let it take you over
column4: ” Garnica reveals. “It’s not necessarily just drugs and alcohol
column5: but our day to day obsessions
column6: relationships
column8: the drama we get involved in and the emotions we feel from it. A lot of the album is about an unhealthy relationship I was in. I felt high about it in the beginning
column9: and it unfortunately reached a point that it was time to quit
column10: but I kept coming back for more.” The band’s subject matter reveals an honest and relatable commentary containing journeys to dark places and coming out of them alive. “We hope this will be your life’s soundtrack for 2015
column11: ” the front man concludes. “It’s been ours for sure.”"	2014-11-09T04:48:03Z	2581994	all	Metal	58585096	True	playlist		2015-08-12T20:38:52Z	all-rights-reserved	[502593420

Dubstep SF is back with Nuratic's super blaster return to the spotlight entitled ""Awakening Project""! Like a dragon awakening from his lair
column2: Nuratic crawls out of his cave dripping with venom and hot lava gnashing his fangs and scratching his claws ready to devour the dance floor with a fresh new belly full of Hot Steaming BASS. Nuratic is a New Jersey born underground legend. Nuratic is a producer
column3: engineer
column4: and dj that dabbles in electro house
column5: trap
column6: and dubstep. Nuratic's debut started at training at Outkast's Stankonia studios in Atlanta. Moving on from there nuratic began to study Sound Engineering at SAE's IT for a degree in audio engineering/music business in atlanta. Nuratic was a resident dj for Atlanta's Largest EDM club
column7: ""Quad"" in Atlanta for two years. At 19 Nuratic won Dim Mak's ""Auh - Auhtorotique"" remix competition which helped put some spotlight onto the releases this artist has made. Nuratic has been through: -Rush Lounge Atlanta GA -Quad Atlantas largest nightclub -Opera Nightclub Atlanta Ga -Kalideoscape -The Works

column1: https://i1.sndcdn.com/artworks-000265480865-yzjgvo-large.jpg	2017-12-05T18:36:01Z	"Visit Joy McDowell's showcase page on The Requatorist! therequatorist.com/jm
Joy McDowell is a graduate of the University of Oregon. She often writes about people at the edge of society
column2: those in rural
column3: blue collar areas who struggle to survive. Her characters don’t attend Vassar or Yale. They hunt and cut meat
column4: sometimes commit crimes and often view life as an experience to outwit. Her latest collection
column5: titled Red Field
column6: is a companion piece to her 2010 collection

column1: She welcomes a reading eye that is interested in the lives of Americans who exist outside the mainstream. Her characters have their own twisted dignity and logic. Like John Steinbeck in his books
column2: Cannery Row and Sweet Thursday
column3: or Carolyn Chute in her book
column4: The Beans of Egypt Maine
column5: Joy McDowell pays close attention to the language and action of what many sources refer to as the lower echelons of American life. Without sentiment she presents her miniature story poems.

column1: Her other chapbooks are Waltzing the Dragon and Blue Cat Shoes. Four of her poems were included in the anthology
column2: New Poets of the American West. Her poem
column3: The Rest I Imagine
column4: was awarded the editor’s choice award for the state of Oregon. She is a member of the Red Sofa Critique group and her work is included in
column5: Mildred
column6: an anthology representing this group of Oregon poets."	2017-12-05T18:36:01Z	313286	all	Poetry	391013201	True	playlist		2017-12-05T18:38:30Z	all-rights-reserved	[]	0	False	joy-mcdowell-1	https://soundcloud.com/user-914801978/sets/joy-mcdowell-1	True	2017-12-05T18:36:01Z			2017-12-05T00:00:00Z	[]	0		compilation	public	therequatorist joymd	Joy McDowell	3	[365403080

column1: https://i1.sndcdn.com/artworks-000172135864-7e41we-large.jpg	2016-07-19T06:43:56Z	"It’s Dragon Suplex’s time now on Dazed & Confused Records. Top producer from Switzerland
column2: Zurich to be exact. Releasing a long stray of releases on labels like Einmusika
column3: Definition:Music and more. He is carving his way to be an underground gem.

column1: This wonderful three tracker starts with the Ep title
column2: Waves Keep Calling Me. A blend of sea waves and high synth progressions. A very emotional track to say the least. Percussions coming in and out as it grooves away in imagination.

column1: Machines is next
column2: a more straight forward cut
column3: just how we like it. You can feel and imagine yourself lost into an industrial path and trying to find your way into the real world. Movement and groove at its best. Dance floor material.

column1: Lastly it’s The Wave
column2: a perfect baseline but melodic oriented track. A mix of beautiful percussions just popping one ofter the other in an experimental way.
